<doc id="212690" wikidata="Q305928" url="?curid=212690" title="Pwd">
<text>In Unix-like and some other operating systems, the codice_1 command (&quot;print working directory&quot;) writes the full pathname of the current working directory to the standard output.

==Implementations==
Multics had a codice_2 command (which was a short name of the codice_3 command) from which the Unix pwd command originated. The command is a shell builtin in most Unix shells such as Bourne shell, ash, bash, ksh, and zsh. It can be implemented easily with the POSIX C functions codice_4 or codice_5.

It is also available in the operating systems SpartaDOS X, PANOS, and KolibriOS. The equivalent on DOS (codice_6) and Microsoft Windows (codice_7) is the codice_8 command with no arguments. Windows PowerShell provides the equivalent codice_9 cmdlet with the standard aliases codice_10 and codice_2.
On Windows CE 5.0, the codice_12 &quot;Command Processor Shell&quot; includes the codice_2 command. 

 as found on Unix systems is part of the X/Open Portability Guide since issue 2 of 1987. It was inherited into the first version of POSIX.1 and the Single Unix Specification. It appeared in Version 5 Unix. The version of codice_2 bundled in GNU coreutils was written by Jim Meyering.

The numerical computing environments MATLAB and GNU Octave include a codice_2 
function with similar functionality. The OpenVMS equivalent is codice_16.

==*nix examples==
Note: POSIX requires that the default behavior be as if the codice_17 switch were provided.

==Working directory shell variables==
POSIX shells set the following environment variables while using the cd command:

; OLDPWD : The previous working directory (as set by the cd command).
; PWD : The current working directory (as set by the cd command).

